  <h1>The SEC Whistleblower Program</h1>
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>Created by the Dodd-Frank Act in 2010, the SEC Whistleblower Program pays 10%–30% of sanctions exceeding $1 million to individuals who provide original, voluntary information about securities law violations. The program is administered by the SEC's Office of the Whistleblower.</p>
  <h2>How to Submit a Tip</h2>
  <p>Submit Form TCR (Tip, Complaint, or Referral) at sec.gov/whistleblower. Tips can be submitted anonymously with attorney representation. You can also submit a preliminary tip to preserve your submission date while gathering more information.</p>
  <h2>What to Report</h2>
  <p>Securities fraud, accounting fraud, insider trading, market manipulation, FCPA violations, Ponzi schemes, investment adviser fraud, and failures by registered entities to comply with federal securities laws.</p>
  <h2>Award Determination</h2>
  <p>The SEC considers: how significant and specific your information was, whether you reported internally first (if this was a factor in the company later reporting), your cooperation during the investigation, and any culpability or unreasonable delay.</p>
  <h2>Anti-Retaliation</h2>
  <p>Dodd-Frank Section 21F prohibits employers from retaliating against employees who report to the SEC. Remedies: reinstatement, double back pay, and attorney fees. These protections apply even if no award is ultimately paid.</p>
